♪ Watching the sun go down ♪

01:00.826 --> 01:05.129
♪ Well, it makes feel like ♪

01:05.197 --> 01:08.866
♪ I'm on my last go 'round ♪

01:08.934 --> 01:11.135
WOMAN: If I had to characterize
the Carter Family

01:11.203 --> 01:14.806
and their music, I would say
it's primal.

01:14.808 --> 01:18.243
It's so rooted.
It's so raw.

01:18.311 --> 01:22.179
It's so spare.
It's so direct.

01:22.247 --> 01:27.185
♪ Well, the water up
on Bear Creek ♪

01:27.286 --> 01:29.787
♪ Tastes like cherry wine ♪

01:29.889 --> 01:33.524
Memphis is the birthplace
of rock 'n' roll,

01:33.626 --> 01:35.593
but then when you go back
farther,

01:35.660 --> 01:38.095
those mountains up there,
the Clinch Mountains...

01:38.163 --> 01:40.532
MAN: That's the starting point
right there, going backwards

01:40.600 --> 01:43.134
all the way to A.P.
and Maybelle and Sara.

01:43.169 --> 01:46.304
LAUDERDALE: They were the first
superstar country group.

01:46.405 --> 01:50.174
♪ One drink of that water ♪

01:50.242 --> 01:53.544
♪ You stay drunk
all the time ♪

01:53.612 --> 01:57.415
People should know who they are
just like they should know

01:57.482 --> 02:00.184
who the first president
of the United States was.

02:00.252 --> 02:02.854
WOMAN: You can say
"the Carter Family" to people,

02:02.922 --> 02:04.622
and they just look at you
with a blank stare,

02:04.690 --> 02:06.557
but if you sing a couple
of the songs --

02:06.625 --> 02:09.293
"Keep On the Sunny Side" or
"Will the Circle Be Unbroken" --

02:09.360 --> 02:11.362
they immediately go, "Oh!"

02:11.430 --> 02:14.532
It's just American.

02:14.534 --> 02:19.037
♪ If you stay up on Bear Creek ♪

02:19.104 --> 02:22.974
♪ You'll get like Jesse James ♪

02:23.109 --> 02:27.178
♪ You'll take two pistols ♪

02:27.246 --> 02:31.349
♪ And rob that Bear Creek
train ♪

02:31.417 --> 02:33.851
HANNA: If you listen
to a Johnny Cash record,

02:33.919 --> 02:35.853
if you're interested
in where it came from,

02:35.921 --> 02:37.822
you're gonna end up
at the Carter Family.

02:37.889 --> 02:39.590
It's not gonna take you
very long.

02:39.658 --> 02:41.058
JOHNNY CASH:
When I was a boy

02:41.126 --> 02:43.695
living in the cotton country
in Arkansas,

02:43.763 --> 02:46.130
at night after working
in the fields,

02:46.199 --> 02:48.265
I had my ear right in
that radio,

02:48.333 --> 02:50.668
and when my Dad would yell
to go to bed,

02:50.736 --> 02:52.369
I would just turn
the volume down

02:52.437 --> 02:54.806
but put my ear closer,
you know,

02:54.873 --> 02:57.341
'cause I had to hear
the Carter Family.

02:57.409 --> 03:03.414
♪ I'm going high ♪

03:03.482 --> 03:07.518
MAN: It's get-togethers,
it's births,

03:07.553 --> 03:09.754
it's funerals --
lots of funerals.

03:09.888 --> 03:11.656
The Carters like the graveyard.

03:11.724 --> 03:14.959
♪ I'm going high ♪

03:15.094 --> 03:18.363
There's nothing standing between
their human heart

03:18.430 --> 03:20.064
and your human ears.

03:20.132 --> 03:22.066
It's a lesson in honesty.

03:22.134 --> 03:26.004
They'll just flat-out expose you
for the faker that you are.

03:26.071 --> 03:27.772
[ laughs ]

03:27.906 --> 03:31.342
ROSANNE CASH: The Carter Family
is like The Beatles

03:31.410 --> 03:34.278
in that threads and fingers
of their music

03:34.347 --> 03:37.715
are woven into everything
that came after them.

03:37.783 --> 03:39.951
You want to hear the real story?

03:40.018 --> 03:42.053
All right. All right.

03:48.327 --> 03:50.829
[ "Bear Creek" ends ]

03:54.332 --> 03:57.869
[ Carter Family's
"Winding Stream" plays ]

04:02.808 --> 04:06.978
♪ Oh, give to me
a winding stream ♪

04:07.045 --> 04:11.149
♪ It must not be too wide ♪

04:11.216 --> 04:15.553
♪ Where waving leaves
from maple trees ♪

04:15.621 --> 04:19.557
♪ Do meet from either side ♪

04:19.625 --> 04:23.928
♪ The water must be
deep enough ♪

04:23.996 --> 04:28.132
♪ To float a small canoe ♪

04:28.200 --> 04:32.770
♪ With no one else but you ♪

04:32.838 --> 04:36.741
♪ Do not disturb ♪

04:36.809 --> 04:41.045
♪ My waking dream ♪

04:41.113 --> 04:45.216
♪ The splendor of ♪

04:45.283 --> 04:49.420
♪ That winding stream ♪

04:49.488 --> 04:53.324
♪ Flower in my canoe ♪

04:53.392 --> 04:57.328
♪ Her eyes, they look me
through ♪

04:57.396 --> 05:01.599
♪ A maiden fair
with golden hair ♪

05:01.667 --> 05:06.604
♪ Looks very much like you... ♪

05:06.672 --> 05:11.976
[ ♪♪ ]

05:12.044 --> 05:13.745
WOMAN: Poor Valley.

05:13.812 --> 05:15.980
Maces Springs, Virginia.

05:16.048 --> 05:20.250
It's, um, God's Country,
I guess you'd say.

05:20.285 --> 05:23.287
♪ Far away on the hills ♪

05:23.355 --> 05:25.657
♪ To a sunny mountainside ♪

05:25.724 --> 05:28.059
♪ Many years ago we parted ♪

05:28.126 --> 05:30.127
♪ My little Ruth and I ♪

05:30.195 --> 05:34.231
♪ From this sunny mountainside ♪

05:34.299 --> 05:38.536
We have family lined up
all the way down the valley.

05:38.604 --> 05:41.472
The whole family was born there,

05:41.540 --> 05:43.674
and they were God-fearing
people.

05:43.743 --> 05:45.810
And they didn't make
a lot of money,

05:45.878 --> 05:48.146
but they would give you
what they had.

05:48.214 --> 05:52.316
♪ Carry me back to old
Virginny ♪

05:52.384 --> 05:56.854
♪ Back to my Clinch Mountain
home ♪

05:56.922 --> 05:59.757
It's hard to make a living
out of a farm --

05:59.824 --> 06:02.426
dirt and the mountains.

06:02.494 --> 06:05.763
Everybody tried to farm,

06:05.830 --> 06:09.967
and most of them had one cow
and a hog or two.

06:09.969 --> 06:12.203
And you put it down on paper,

06:12.205 --> 06:14.572
it sounds like you was
very rich.

06:14.639 --> 06:16.807
We probably was rich.

06:16.809 --> 06:18.976
It wasn't money-wise,

06:19.044 --> 06:23.081
but it sure was a different
way of life to what it is now.

06:23.115 --> 06:27.652
♪ At my old Clinch Mountain
home ♪

06:27.654 --> 06:29.620
My daddy was pleasant.

06:29.688 --> 06:32.356
His name was Alvin Pleasant
Carter.

06:32.424 --> 06:35.927
WOMAN: My granddad grew up
different from other children.

06:36.028 --> 06:38.663
He only went, really, to about
the third grade.

06:38.730 --> 06:39.831
And the children, of course,

06:39.898 --> 06:42.033
made fun of his tremor
in his hands.

06:42.101 --> 06:45.370
And, of course, he was
an extremely sensitive child.

06:45.437 --> 06:47.137
JANETTE CARTER:
My daddy liked to walk

06:47.205 --> 06:49.673
up and down the railroads.

06:49.742 --> 06:53.277
And he'd always have his hands
behind his back.

06:53.344 --> 06:55.112
WOMAN: A lot of times
you'd pass him,

06:55.180 --> 06:58.449
and you'd say something to him,
and he didn't hardly answer you.

06:58.517 --> 07:00.618
He was always in deep thought.

07:00.686 --> 07:03.721
JANETTE CARTER:
He was a very kind man.

07:03.789 --> 07:05.690
Unless he got mad,

07:05.758 --> 07:07.559
and if got mad, you better
let him alone,

07:07.626 --> 07:09.928
'cause he had a temper.

07:09.995 --> 07:11.996
He never did spank me
but three times,

07:12.064 --> 07:14.732
but I remember all of 'em.

07:14.800 --> 07:16.300
And he wasn't a great farmer.

07:16.368 --> 07:18.002
I know one of my neighbors
said to me once,

07:18.036 --> 07:19.838
said, "A.P.'s not
a very good farmer."

07:19.905 --> 07:22.574
And it irritated me that he'd
say something about my uncle,

07:22.641 --> 07:26.778
and I said, "No, and you or I
can't write songs either."

07:29.181 --> 07:33.384
[ playing "I'm in Your Care" ]

07:33.452 --> 07:39.123
♪ Oh, Lord, I'm in your care ♪

07:39.191 --> 07:44.528
♪ Oh, Lord,
I'm in your care ♪

07:44.597 --> 07:47.598
♪ Your loving arms around me ♪

07:47.666 --> 07:50.201
♪ Evil cannot harm me ♪

07:50.268 --> 07:54.305
♪ Oh, Lord, I'm in your care ♪

07:54.372 --> 07:59.410
♪ When I was sick,
I was in your care ♪

07:59.478 --> 08:04.215
♪ When I was sick, I was
in your care ♪

08:04.282 --> 08:08.486
FORRESTER: In 1906, A.P.,
his father, and his brothers

08:08.553 --> 08:11.122
helped to actually take timber
out of Clinch Mountain

08:11.189 --> 08:14.092
to erect Mt. Vernon Church,

08:14.094 --> 08:15.659
which is the church that now

08:15.727 --> 08:18.829
I guess the seventh generation
of Carter children attend.

08:18.864 --> 08:22.500
♪ I'm a reckless child,
but I'm in your care ♪

08:22.568 --> 08:26.170
My granddad, he had this deep,
deep religious upbringing

08:26.238 --> 08:29.173
and attended a lot
of singing schools,

08:29.241 --> 08:31.975
sang in the choir
at Mt. Vernon Church.

08:31.977 --> 08:34.044
He started out playing
the fiddle,

08:34.113 --> 08:35.780
but that bothered his mother

08:35.847 --> 08:40.051
because she thought the fiddle
was a devil's instrument.

08:40.119 --> 08:46.290
♪ Lord, I'm in your care ♪

08:46.358 --> 08:49.694
A.P. Carter had an amazing
and inspired love for music.

08:49.761 --> 08:51.762
It carried him, it drove him.

08:51.830 --> 08:53.864
I truly believe that the reason

08:53.932 --> 08:55.966
that he became
a traveling salesman

08:56.034 --> 08:58.669
was so that he could go
from town to town,

08:58.737 --> 09:00.838
front porch to front porch,

09:00.905 --> 09:03.073
train yard to train yard,

09:03.141 --> 09:06.043
to meet different people,
different walks of life,

09:06.110 --> 09:08.479
and pick up songs along the way.

09:08.547 --> 09:13.184
[ opening of "Engine 143"
plays ]

09:15.887 --> 09:18.456
FORRESTER: My granddad, he
walked across Clinch Mountain,

09:18.524 --> 09:21.526
which would take you
a good full day.

09:21.593 --> 09:24.128
And at that time he was selling
fruit trees.

09:24.196 --> 09:27.731
So he would just go to different
houses to sell these trees.

09:27.799 --> 09:31.869
And he came into the yard
where she lived,

09:31.936 --> 09:35.573
and he heard a woman singing
and playing the autoharp.

09:35.707 --> 09:38.242
And she was singing
"Engine 143."

09:38.309 --> 09:41.913
♪ The doctor said to Georgie ♪

09:41.980 --> 09:45.650
♪ Your life cannot be saved ♪

09:45.717 --> 09:48.920
♪ Murdered upon the railroad ♪

09:48.987 --> 09:52.356
♪ And laid in a lonesome grave ♪

09:52.424 --> 09:56.794
♪ His face was covered up
with blood ♪

09:56.862 --> 10:00.364
♪ His eyes you could not see ♪

10:00.432 --> 10:04.835
♪ And the very last words
poor Georgie said ♪

10:04.903 --> 10:08.372
♪ Was nearer, my God, to Thee ♪

10:08.474 --> 10:10.808
And he said he stood and
listened for a long time,

10:10.876 --> 10:13.510
and he thought it was the most
beautiful thing he'd ever heard.

10:13.578 --> 10:15.079
And he introduced himself

10:15.146 --> 10:18.315
and told her he was there
to sell some fruit trees.

10:18.384 --> 10:20.852
And she let him know
that she was selling dishes,

10:20.919 --> 10:23.954
and would he like to buy
some of her dishes.

10:24.022 --> 10:26.657
He told her that
if she came with him,

10:26.725 --> 10:28.793
he'd take the entire set.

10:31.529 --> 10:33.463
They married fairly young.

10:33.531 --> 10:37.268
I think she was just... not much
more than 16, going on 17,

10:37.335 --> 10:40.604
and he was a few years older.

10:40.672 --> 10:42.739
But they married and then,
of course,

10:42.808 --> 10:45.509
moved to this side
of the mountain.

10:50.982 --> 10:53.483
Fern, watch these thistles,
honey.

10:53.551 --> 10:56.453
- They'll stick in ya.
- Yeah, I know.

10:56.521 --> 10:58.155
- You see that gate up there?
- Yeah, I see that gate.

10:58.223 --> 10:59.657
We come down the break
of the hill,

10:59.725 --> 11:01.091
and then we'd walk down
thataway.

11:01.159 --> 11:03.093
That's the only way I came
as a child.

11:03.161 --> 11:05.797
That'd be a lot closer.

11:05.864 --> 11:08.866
Look, here's an old part
of a bedstead.

11:08.934 --> 11:10.301
Yeah.

11:10.368 --> 11:12.369
You know, Aunt Sara may have --

11:12.437 --> 11:14.872
she might have even slept
in this, did you know it?

11:14.940 --> 11:17.441
She could have, that bed.

11:17.509 --> 11:19.110
People, we'll have to be
careful.

11:19.178 --> 11:20.878
The porch is just about gone.

11:20.946 --> 11:23.147
Please watch your step.

11:23.215 --> 11:28.052
[ opening of
"Picture on the Wall" plays ]

11:30.989 --> 11:34.225
FORRESTER: My grandmother
lost her mother at about age 3.

11:34.293 --> 11:36.593
Her mother died.

11:36.661 --> 11:39.430
When her mother passed away,

11:39.497 --> 11:42.566
her father kept the three sons
with him

11:42.634 --> 11:47.604
and gave her and her sister
to an aunt to raise.

11:47.672 --> 11:51.409
And that had to have a very
profound effect on her,

11:51.476 --> 11:53.844
you know, growing up
without her mother.

11:53.946 --> 11:59.016
♪ There's an old and faded
picture on the wall ♪

11:59.084 --> 12:04.288
♪ That has been a-hanging there
for many a-year ♪

12:04.356 --> 12:06.891
♪ 'Tis a picture of my mother ♪

12:06.958 --> 12:09.593
♪ For I know there is no other ♪

12:09.661 --> 12:14.832
♪ That can take the place
of mother on the wall ♪

12:14.900 --> 12:17.502
♪ On the wall ♪
♪ On the wall ♪

12:17.569 --> 12:20.071
♪ On the wall ♪
♪ On the wall ♪

12:20.172 --> 12:24.975
♪ How I love that dear old
picture on the wall ♪

12:25.043 --> 12:27.645
And of course Aunt Maybelle
and my grandmother

12:27.712 --> 12:29.680
were first cousins

12:29.748 --> 12:32.983
and grew up pretty much together
and were making music

12:33.051 --> 12:35.853
from the time they were
little girls together.

12:35.920 --> 12:37.822
WOMAN: Just like any other
country girl.

12:37.889 --> 12:40.057
They put up pickles,
they canned, they churned,

12:40.125 --> 12:42.426
they had cows, did a garden,

12:42.494 --> 12:44.996
I'd say just like everybody else
in this country.

12:45.063 --> 12:47.264
Just a hard, but good life.

12:47.332 --> 12:52.169
MAN: Sara and Maybelle,
they were first cousins.

12:52.237 --> 12:55.306
And they married brothers.

12:55.374 --> 12:58.942
So that made us kids almost
double first, you know,

12:59.010 --> 13:02.913
about one and three-quarter,
I guess you'd call it.

13:02.981 --> 13:05.616
JOHN CARTER CASH:
A.P. and Sara and Maybelle

13:05.684 --> 13:09.553
were very different people,
there's no doubt.

13:09.655 --> 13:13.791
But they had a unique and
beautiful shared love for music.

13:13.892 --> 13:16.260
Maybelle and Sara probably
weren't quite as serious

13:16.327 --> 13:17.928
about it in the beginning,

13:17.996 --> 13:19.696
and I think A.P. gave 'em
a little push

13:19.765 --> 13:21.265
and got them to look
at the possibility

13:21.332 --> 13:24.735
that this might end up being
their career.

13:24.803 --> 13:28.672
[ ♪♪ ]

13:46.124 --> 13:47.858
MAN: Back in the 1920s,

13:47.926 --> 13:50.961
the record companies had gotten
interested in recording

13:51.029 --> 13:53.364
what they called
"old time" music.

13:53.432 --> 13:56.233
They didn't use the word
"country" back in those days.

13:56.301 --> 13:59.970
But the idea was it was kind of
folk music from the mountains.

14:00.038 --> 14:03.607
And so Ralph Peer was hired
by RCA Victor

14:03.675 --> 14:05.742
to go after this music.

14:05.810 --> 14:08.846
WOMAN: Ralph Peer took a chance
to say, "Okay,

14:08.848 --> 14:11.348
let's go down and see
what's down here and record it

14:11.416 --> 14:14.951
and see if anybody will buy
this stuff."

14:15.053 --> 14:19.189
CHARLES WOLFE: So he took off
in the summer of 1927.

14:19.258 --> 14:21.459
His idea was to go into
these towns,

14:21.526 --> 14:23.594
set up a temporary studio,

14:23.662 --> 14:26.596
and try to lure people in
for recordings.

14:26.698 --> 14:30.300
And he arrived in Bristol
in late July,

14:30.368 --> 14:33.904
and he thinks, "I really need
now to go cattle call

14:33.971 --> 14:36.440
and see who I can bring out."

14:36.508 --> 14:40.377
[ ♪♪ ]

14:55.126 --> 14:57.627
They were answering an ad
they found in the paper

14:57.695 --> 14:59.829
from Ralph Peer.

14:59.897 --> 15:03.668
The ad was asking musicians
and singers to come

15:03.735 --> 15:07.605
and make records for
Victor Talking Machine Company.

15:07.639 --> 15:09.473
FORRESTER: My granddad, of
course, he didn't have a car.

15:09.541 --> 15:13.311
He ended up borrowing Maybelle's
husband's car, Uncle Eck's car.

15:13.378 --> 15:16.213
And Aunt Maybelle was
eight months pregnant.

15:16.281 --> 15:18.849
I imagine the very last thing
she wanted to do

15:18.917 --> 15:21.785
was go to Bristol in
the scorching August heat.

15:21.853 --> 15:23.721
JOHNNY CASH:
They got ready to go,

15:23.788 --> 15:27.758
and A.P. asked Maybelle
if she had her guitar.

15:27.825 --> 15:30.093
And she said, "No, I don't
need that, do I?"

15:30.161 --> 15:33.497
And he said, "Yeah, better bring
your guitar."

15:33.532 --> 15:38.402
So Maybelle, A.P., and I,
we decided we'd go up.

15:38.470 --> 15:41.305
Of course, we didn't think
anything about it,

15:41.372 --> 15:45.142
just thought it more or less
just a trip.

15:45.210 --> 15:47.244
CHARLES WOLFE: And they were
supposed to have gotten there

15:47.311 --> 15:49.113
in the afternoon.

15:49.181 --> 15:52.449
Even though it's not a very
long drive to Bristol today,

15:52.517 --> 15:55.485
back in those days they had
to go on dirt roads,

15:55.487 --> 15:58.088
and so they had all kinds
of problems.

15:58.155 --> 16:02.426
They had to forge streams,
it was hot, they had blowouts.

16:02.494 --> 16:05.729
They didn't get into Bristol
until that evening.

16:05.797 --> 16:08.332
But when they showed up,
Peer said,

16:08.400 --> 16:11.935
"Come on over anyway, and let's
try to get some work done."

16:12.003 --> 16:14.338
Their first sessions were
actually held

16:14.406 --> 16:17.307
in a temporary studio
down on Main Street,

16:17.375 --> 16:20.110
on the second floor
of a hat company.

16:20.178 --> 16:23.414
Ralph Peer was in a little
glassed-in room,

16:23.482 --> 16:26.016
and he would press a button.

16:26.084 --> 16:29.453
The light would go on red
and then it would go to green,

16:29.520 --> 16:33.557
and then they would start
singing.

16:33.624 --> 16:37.995
♪ Oh, bury me under
the weeping willow ♪

16:38.063 --> 16:42.366
♪ Yes, under the weeping willow
tree ♪

16:42.434 --> 16:46.737
♪ So he may know
where I am sleeping ♪

16:46.805 --> 16:50.841
♪ And perhaps he will
weep for me ♪

16:50.843 --> 16:53.109
In those days, they didn't have
different microphones

16:53.177 --> 16:54.445
for each singer.

16:54.512 --> 16:56.180
And they very quickly found out

16:56.247 --> 16:58.382
that Sara's voice was
really powerful.

16:58.450 --> 17:02.352
♪ I hear a low faint voice
that says ♪

17:02.420 --> 17:06.623
♪ Papa and Mama's dead ♪

17:06.625 --> 17:10.761
♪ And it comes from
the poor orphan child ♪

17:10.828 --> 17:14.998
♪ That must be clothed and fed ♪

17:15.000 --> 17:17.901
A.P. never did really sing
very loud.

17:17.969 --> 17:20.637
He would stand in back of them
and kind of move around

17:20.704 --> 17:23.107
and every now and then lean in
and, as he said,

17:23.175 --> 17:25.242
do a little "bassin' in."

17:25.310 --> 17:29.413
♪ Savior,
lead them by the hand ♪

17:29.481 --> 17:33.050
♪ Savior, lead them
by the hand ♪

17:53.004 --> 17:55.472
CHARLES WOLFE:
So they recorded four songs

17:55.574 --> 17:59.843
in about 90 minutes that night,
and Peer was very pleased.

17:59.911 --> 18:01.811
So he said, "We would like
for you to come back

18:01.880 --> 18:03.446
and do some more songs
tomorrow morning.

18:03.514 --> 18:04.681
Could you do that?"

18:04.749 --> 18:06.183
And they said, "Yes, we can."

18:06.251 --> 18:09.220
And the next morning, he goes in
to meet the Carters,

18:09.287 --> 18:12.389
and lo and behold,
A.P. has gone missing,

18:12.457 --> 18:15.626
and only Sara and Maybelle
are there.

18:15.628 --> 18:20.230
And then she says, "We can do
the songs ourselves okay."

18:20.298 --> 18:22.265
And he says, "Well, okay."

18:22.333 --> 18:26.470
And I know we made
"Single Girl, Married Girl,"

18:26.538 --> 18:28.305
and I didn't want to sing
that song.

18:28.373 --> 18:29.640
I didn't like it.

18:29.674 --> 18:31.941
And I told Mr. Peer, I says,
"I don't like that.

18:32.009 --> 18:33.477
I'd rather not sing that."

18:33.544 --> 18:35.879
"Oh," he says, "I want you
to sing that."

18:35.946 --> 18:39.516
So I sung "The Single Girl"
solo.

18:39.518 --> 18:43.454
♪ Single girl, single girl ♪

18:43.521 --> 18:46.523
♪ She's going dressed fine ♪

18:46.590 --> 18:49.993
CHARLES WOLFE: Sara began
singing her song "Single Girl,"

18:50.061 --> 18:53.797
