23:27.037 --> 23:29.605
FORRESTER: My granddad would go
anywhere to hunt a song.

23:29.673 --> 23:31.841
And he'd go for weeks at a time.

23:31.943 --> 23:33.744
At that time, songs were things

23:33.811 --> 23:37.046
that people traded,
exchanged, shared.

23:37.114 --> 23:39.583
It wasn't like anyone
owned a song.

23:39.650 --> 23:41.084
It was a community thing.

23:41.152 --> 23:42.786
It belonged to everybody.

23:42.854 --> 23:44.354
And they told stories.

23:44.422 --> 23:47.924
I mean, that's how they handed
down their history, was by song.

23:47.992 --> 23:53.263
♪ I'm worried now,
but I won't be worried long ♪

23:53.330 --> 23:55.832
ROSANNE CASH: When we look
at what happened

23:55.900 --> 23:58.501
from our vantage point
in the 21st century,

23:58.570 --> 24:01.337
it seems alarming somewhat

24:01.406 --> 24:04.173
that A.P. went and collected
these songs.

24:04.275 --> 24:06.243
But the fact that
he collected them

24:06.310 --> 24:09.913
saved them from obscurity.

24:09.981 --> 24:13.583
[ playing folk tune ]

