♪ Trying to make up
all of her lost time ♪

34:24.762 --> 34:28.598
The Carter Family were there at
the height of the power of XERA.

34:28.666 --> 34:33.335
And Dr. Brinkley actually pays
them $75 a week to perform.

34:33.404 --> 34:36.906
So they are the royalty
on the border radio station,

34:36.973 --> 34:38.608
because they don't have
to pull the mail.

34:38.676 --> 34:40.610
They're getting paid.

34:40.678 --> 34:42.745
JOHNNY CASH: The first time
I heard the Carter Family

34:42.813 --> 34:47.750
was on border radio, and I
thought it was wonderful music.

34:47.818 --> 34:51.454
ROSANNE CASH: He actually got
the signal from Arkansas

34:51.522 --> 34:53.956
and heard little June Carter,

34:54.024 --> 34:56.324
you know, when she was
a preteen.

34:56.393 --> 35:00.196
♪ Beautiful, beautiful
brown eyes ♪

35:00.263 --> 35:03.999
♪ Beautiful, beautiful brown
eyes ♪

35:04.067 --> 35:07.337
♪ Beautiful, beautiful
brown eyes ♪

35:07.404 --> 35:10.673
♪ I'll never love blue eyes
again ♪

35:10.741 --> 35:16.212
CRAWFORD: The Carter kids were
child stars of the era, really.

35:16.313 --> 35:18.648
And they really started
pulling the mail,

35:18.716 --> 35:22.118
as many as 25,000 letters
a week.

35:22.153 --> 35:25.020
JANETTE CARTER: Helen, June,
and Anita sung together.

35:25.089 --> 35:28.224
I sung solos by myself.

35:28.292 --> 35:31.360
I was 16 years old.

35:31.428 --> 35:35.098
It bothered my parents to be
away from their children,

35:35.165 --> 35:38.534
and that's the reason they put
us on the program, I guess,

35:38.602 --> 35:43.740
to keep my parents from going
back home and not coming back.

35:43.807 --> 35:47.643
[ ♪♪ ]

35:47.711 --> 35:50.312
CRAWFORD: A.P. and Sara were
split up at this time,

35:50.380 --> 35:51.981
and you could really feel
the tension

35:52.049 --> 35:53.616
in their music and their
performances.

35:53.684 --> 35:56.385
There was a lot of sadness,
there was a lot of heartache.

35:56.453 --> 35:59.889
It wasn't a happy family.

35:59.957 --> 36:04.627
♪ It would have been better
for us both had we never ♪

36:04.694 --> 36:08.531
♪ In this wide and wicked world
had never met ♪

36:08.598 --> 36:10.333
LAURA CASH:
Sara was very unhappy

36:10.401 --> 36:12.402
at the border radio stations,

36:12.436 --> 36:14.703
and out of the blue one night
on the radio,

36:14.771 --> 36:16.972
she sent out a song
to Coy Bays,

36:17.040 --> 36:20.609
"I'm Thinking Tonight
of My Blue Eyes."

36:20.677 --> 36:23.412
She hadn't talked to him
in six years

36:23.480 --> 36:26.182
and just wondered if he'd be
listening.

36:26.250 --> 36:30.319
♪ Oh, I'm thinking tonight
of my blue eyes ♪

36:30.387 --> 36:34.757
♪ And I wonder if he ever
thinks of me ♪

36:34.825 --> 36:38.094
Border radio, of course,
transmitted all over America,

36:38.162 --> 36:39.628
and sure enough, he heard it.

36:39.696 --> 36:42.231
He was with his parents
in California

36:42.299 --> 36:46.535
and came in and told his mom and
dad, "I'm going to get her."

36:46.604 --> 36:50.306
So Coy loads up and drives
to Texas

36:50.341 --> 36:54.010
and takes his bride, and they
were married within a week.

36:54.077 --> 36:57.046
JOE CARTER: My daddy, he didn't
approve of that, you know.

36:57.314 --> 37:00.883
He hated when the other man
was his cousin,

37:00.951 --> 37:02.318
first cousin, you know.

37:02.385 --> 37:04.119
Growing up, all that we knew

37:04.187 --> 37:06.389
was that it hurt my granddad
to talk about it,

37:06.457 --> 37:08.925
and therefore, we didn't talk
about it.

37:08.993 --> 37:13.029
♪ But a link in the chain
has been broken ♪

37:13.096 --> 37:18.267
♪ Leaves me with a sad
and aching heart ♪

37:18.335 --> 37:23.072
[ ♪♪ ]

37:38.655 --> 37:40.489
FORRESTER: When she left,

37:40.557 --> 37:43.426
she was thinking of what
was best for her children.

37:43.493 --> 37:46.662
And she knew that her children
with their father

37:46.730 --> 37:48.764
had a wonderful support system

37:48.832 --> 37:52.101
and that they had his mother,
they had his sisters,

37:52.168 --> 37:55.071
they had, you know, basically
what they needed.

37:55.138 --> 37:58.240
And I guess she knew that they
had everything they needed here

37:58.308 --> 38:00.676
and that she could not
give them that.

38:00.743 --> 38:04.547
I'm sure she was judged
very harshly by a lot of people,

38:04.614 --> 38:06.382
and I imagine that's one reason

38:06.450 --> 38:10.720
that the distance gave her
some comfort.

38:10.787 --> 38:14.857
[ ♪♪ ]

38:19.195 --> 38:23.332
CHARLES WOLFE: A photographer
from LIFE magazine decided that

38:23.400 --> 38:26.769
they wanted to do a feature
on the Carter Family,

38:26.803 --> 38:30.973
and they went up into Maces
Springs and shot the pictures.

38:31.041 --> 38:32.174
[ shutter clicks ]

38:35.746 --> 38:36.979
[ shutter clicks ]

38:39.149 --> 38:40.349
[ shutter clicks ]

38:42.119 --> 38:43.019
[ shutter clicks ]

38:49.893 --> 38:54.464
And June remembers he filled
a whole wastebasket full

38:54.531 --> 38:57.533
of those big old-fashioned
flash bulbs.

38:57.600 --> 39:02.104
The problem was they were
scheduled to do that story

39:02.172 --> 39:07.376
in LIFE magazine for the issue
of December 7, 1941.

39:07.443 --> 39:09.812
And of course it never got run.

39:09.880 --> 39:13.615
CLIFTON: And the Japanese
bombed Pearl Harbor.

39:13.683 --> 39:17.686
My theory is that the Carters
were bombed out of their career.

39:17.754 --> 39:22.625
I think if that LIFE magazine
had come out as planned,

39:22.693 --> 39:26.161
there would have been
an incredible amount of work

39:26.229 --> 39:28.831
for the Carters
all over this country.

39:28.899 --> 39:30.766
CHARLES WOLFE:
With the war starting up,

39:30.834 --> 39:34.303
the kind of sentimental
songs of home,

39:34.371 --> 39:36.238
they would have been heard
overseas,

39:36.306 --> 39:40.242
they would have won thousands of
new fans all over the country.

39:40.310 --> 39:42.745
But it didn't happen.

39:42.846 --> 39:47.049
It was a kind of cusp
in their career.

39:47.117 --> 39:50.319
And Maybelle was the only one
of the bunch

39:50.386 --> 39:55.057
that really saw the future
in professional country music.

39:55.125 --> 39:57.459
And once she got her kids
to where

39:57.527 --> 40:00.395
they could sing pretty well,
she immediately took off

40:00.463 --> 40:03.665
and started forging
her own career.

40:03.667 --> 40:05.634
[ ♪♪ ]

40:05.702 --> 40:07.503
ROSANNE CASH:
Maybelle had three daughters:

40:07.570 --> 40:09.438
Helen, Anita, and June.

40:09.506 --> 40:11.640
And after the original
Carter Family

40:11.708 --> 40:13.276
wasn't performing anymore,

40:13.343 --> 40:15.278
Maybelle took them on the road
with her,

40:15.345 --> 40:18.447
and it was Mother Maybelle
and the Carter Sisters.

40:18.515 --> 40:21.617
They were very young
when they started this.

40:21.685 --> 40:23.952
I think maybe June was 9.

40:24.020 --> 40:26.988
And, Anita, I think was still
sleeping in guitar cases

40:27.056 --> 40:29.491
at this point.

40:29.559 --> 40:33.930
By the time I got to know Helen
and Anita and June and Maybelle,

40:33.997 --> 40:36.866
I was 10 years old, maybe.

40:36.934 --> 40:41.537
And they had virtually been
on the road their entire lives.

40:41.604 --> 40:46.508
[ playing
"The Wildwood Flower" ]

40:46.576 --> 40:52.348
♪ Oh, I'll twine with my mingles
and waving black hair ♪

40:52.416 --> 40:58.287
♪ With the roses so red
and the lilies so fair ♪

40:58.355 --> 41:03.559
♪ And the myrtle so bright
with the emerald dew ♪

41:03.627 --> 41:07.896
♪ The pale and the leader
and eyes look like blue ♪

41:07.964 --> 41:10.832
Maybelle invented
the Carter scratch,

41:10.968 --> 41:13.936
where she could play lead guitar
and rhythm guitar

41:14.004 --> 41:15.271
at the same time.

41:15.339 --> 41:17.139
Nobody else did that.

41:17.207 --> 41:18.907
Because it was just
the three of them,

41:18.976 --> 41:20.742
A.P. and Sara and Maybelle,

41:20.810 --> 41:23.245
she invented that
out of necessity.

41:23.313 --> 41:27.349
Her guitar playing on "The
Wildwood Flower" is phenomenal.

41:27.417 --> 41:28.818
It's quintessential.

41:28.885 --> 41:31.821
It should be in the Smithsonian,
that guitar part.

41:53.443 --> 41:59.281
♪ Oh, he taught me to love him
and promised to love... ♪

41:59.349 --> 42:03.085
When I would see them backstage
or before doing a show,

42:03.153 --> 42:06.888
I was struck by this naturalness
they had about them.

42:06.957 --> 42:10.359
♪ I'm wondering
no misery can tell ♪

42:10.427 --> 42:12.595
♪ He's left me no warning... ♪

42:12.663 --> 42:16.532
They had their bag of shoes and
their clothes and their makeup,

42:16.600 --> 42:19.668
and they just kind of did
this ritual

42:19.736 --> 42:23.806
that had no angst about it or no
performance anxiety, or nothing.

42:23.873 --> 42:26.375
It was just part of
what they did.

42:26.443 --> 42:28.777
It was so natural.

42:30.447 --> 42:34.983
They just brought their selves
to every performance.

42:35.051 --> 42:37.653
I've carried that with me
into adulthood,

42:37.721 --> 42:39.921
into my own life
as a performer,

42:39.989 --> 42:43.425
the lack of anxiety,
the naturalness about it,

42:43.493 --> 42:44.593
the bag of shoes.

42:44.661 --> 42:46.529
[ laughs ]

42:46.596 --> 42:47.930
Let's everybody smack
their hands

42:47.998 --> 42:49.999
for Mother Maybelle
and the Carter Sisters.

42:50.067 --> 42:53.469
[ cheers and applause ]

42:58.208 --> 43:03.479
[ Carter Sisters singing
"Sweet Talkin' Man" ]

43:05.782 --> 43:07.783
JOHN CARTER CASH: Chet worked
with them for years,

43:07.851 --> 43:11.920
and he had quite a reputation as
being an amazing guitar player.

43:11.955 --> 43:14.690
When it came time that
they got a big offer

43:14.758 --> 43:18.293
from the Grand Ole Opry
to move to Nashville,

43:18.362 --> 43:20.129
it was suggested that
they didn't bring

43:20.196 --> 43:21.997
Mr. Atkins with them.

43:22.099 --> 43:25.333
They thought he was a little
too jazzy for the Opry.

43:25.369 --> 43:28.337
My grandpa Ezra,
he made the deals.

43:28.405 --> 43:30.806
He said, "Well, you get
the whole kit and caboodle

43:30.874 --> 43:32.608
or you don't get anything."

43:32.676 --> 43:34.709
JOHN CARTER CASH:
In the end, they won out,

43:34.777 --> 43:37.780
and Chet moved to Nashville with
Maybelle and the Carter girls

43:37.848 --> 43:39.915
and began his stint on
the Grand Ole Opry with them,

43:39.983 --> 43:42.384
and the rest is history.

43:51.828 --> 43:55.464
♪ And if he told me that
he thought I could fly... ♪

43:55.532 --> 43:57.766
WOMAN:
Helen was the glue.

43:57.834 --> 44:00.302
She made everything work

44:00.369 --> 44:02.938
in the sense of anything
was missing,

44:03.006 --> 44:04.773
Helen could play it
or sing it.

44:04.874 --> 44:09.311
She was probably the best
songwriter of all of them.

44:09.378 --> 44:11.146
♪ Sweet talkin' man ♪

44:11.214 --> 44:13.148
♪ I can't be free ♪

44:13.216 --> 44:16.585
♪ And I don't care if he hasn't
got a dime ♪

44:16.653 --> 44:21.056
♪ All I need to know is that
he's all mine ♪

44:21.124 --> 44:22.358
♪ I got a man... ♪

44:22.426 --> 44:24.026
SALYER:
And Anita was the singer.

44:24.094 --> 44:25.827
There's just no greater voice.

44:25.895 --> 44:27.062
She could do it all.

44:27.130 --> 44:28.864
She could hit the high notes
that nobody could touch,

44:28.932 --> 44:30.799
and she did it in such
a beautiful sound.

44:30.901 --> 44:38.407
♪ Today I passed you
on the street ♪

44:38.475 --> 44:44.312
♪ And my heart fell
at your feet ♪

44:44.381 --> 44:53.655
♪ I can't help it if I'm still
in love with you ♪

44:53.723 --> 45:01.430
♪ Somebody else stood
by your side ♪

45:01.498 --> 45:06.869
♪ And he looked
so satisfied... ♪

45:06.936 --> 45:09.872
SALYER: Anita had more of
a pop sound voice,

45:09.939 --> 45:12.775
but she never pushed
her career,

45:12.842 --> 45:14.743
but she had a beautiful voice

45:14.811 --> 45:18.246
that she never fulfilled to
the limit, I never thought.

45:18.315 --> 45:19.881
DAVIS: She was way ahead
of her time, I think,

45:19.949 --> 45:21.550
as far as her voice,

45:21.618 --> 45:24.620
and definitely everybody
in the music business anyway

45:24.721 --> 45:26.655
knew what she was capable
of doing

45:26.723 --> 45:28.824
and knew that she could do it.

45:28.892 --> 45:39.134
♪ I can't help it if I'm still
in love with you ♪

45:39.201 --> 45:40.869
Family was very important
to her,

45:40.937 --> 45:43.304
and she chose to stay
with the family,

45:43.372 --> 45:44.673
and to the day she died,

45:44.741 --> 45:47.576
that was what she was happy
with doing.

45:47.644 --> 45:49.745
Ladies and gentlemen,
June Carter.

45:49.813 --> 45:52.147
Thank you.

45:52.215 --> 45:54.883
Thanks, y'all.

45:54.951 --> 45:56.384
Yeah, no kiddin', folks.

45:56.452 --> 45:58.687
Y'all don't know just what
it means for me

45:58.755 --> 46:00.956
to get to be on this show
here tonight.

46:01.024 --> 46:04.326
It means a lot more than
the prestige of the thing,

46:04.393 --> 46:08.530
or it means more than applause.

46:08.598 --> 46:10.699
It means money,
is what it means.

46:10.766 --> 46:12.968
Oh, no, June, June, honey,
you shouldn't say that.

46:13.036 --> 46:14.503
JOHN CARTER CASH:
My mother always had

46:14.571 --> 46:16.004
an amazing sense of humor.

46:16.072 --> 46:19.140
And early on she realized
that she didn't have the talent

46:19.208 --> 46:22.010
of playing guitar
that her sister Helen had.

46:22.078 --> 46:24.680
She didn't have the voice
that Anita had.

46:24.748 --> 46:26.782
CARLENE CARTER:
She wanted to be an actress.

46:26.850 --> 46:29.251
She wanted to be an entertainer.

46:29.318 --> 46:31.787
Because she didn't think she was
a very good singer,

46:32.055 --> 46:36.391
she found a way to entertain,
and that was through her comedy.

46:36.459 --> 46:38.994
SALYER: You know, everybody said
June wasn't a singer.

46:39.061 --> 46:41.162
June would say it,
"I'm not a singer."

46:41.230 --> 46:43.465
But she had the stage
personality

46:43.532 --> 46:45.134
that everybody loved.

46:45.201 --> 46:47.269
♪ On Saturday night
where I was born ♪

46:47.336 --> 46:49.204
♪ Down on the farm ♪

46:49.272 --> 46:51.172
♪ Guitars pickin'
and we start singin' ♪

46:51.240 --> 46:52.942
♪ Till the break of dawn ♪

46:53.009 --> 46:55.010
♪ About 12 o'clock everything
gets hot ♪

46:55.078 --> 46:57.078
♪ And up steps ole Jones ♪

46:57.146 --> 46:59.014
♪ We start a-clappin'
and he starts singin' ♪

46:59.082 --> 47:01.083
♪ A cute little country song ♪

47:01.217 --> 47:03.319
♪ Boll Weevil, Boll Weevil ♪

47:03.386 --> 47:05.154
♪ Why'd you go and stay? ♪

47:05.221 --> 47:07.189
♪ You'll get a lickin'
as sure as I'm sittin' ♪

47:07.257 --> 47:09.892
♪ On this bale of hay ♪

47:12.061 --> 47:16.398
[ whistling and cheering ]

47:25.775 --> 47:28.276
♪ On Saturday night
where I was born ♪

47:28.344 --> 47:30.713
♪ Down on the farm... ♪

47:30.780 --> 47:36.185
I met June Carter backstage
at the Grand Ole Opry in 1956,

47:36.252 --> 47:40.322
and I met Mother Maybelle,
Helen, and Anita.

47:40.389 --> 47:42.625
Of course, I fell in love
with that June,

47:42.692 --> 47:45.461
that red-headed one,
that dancer,

47:45.528 --> 47:48.697
the one that pulled the jokes,
the funny one.

47:48.732 --> 47:51.967
She stole my heart right away,
right away.

47:52.068 --> 47:55.771
That night I told her, I said,

47:55.839 --> 47:58.640
"I'm going to marry you
someday."

47:58.742 --> 48:03.178
But at the time, we were both
with somebody else.

48:03.246 --> 48:08.250
[ song ends and crowd cheers
and applauds ]

48:11.154 --> 48:15.657
[ opening of Johnny Cash's
"Big River" plays ]

48:17.827 --> 48:23.365
♪ Now I taught the weeping
willow how to cry ♪

48:23.433 --> 48:28.604
♪ And I showed the clouds how
to cover up a clear blue sky ♪

48:28.672 --> 48:31.273
♪ And the tears that I cried
for that woman ♪

48:31.341 --> 48:34.009
♪ Are gonna flood you,
Big River ♪

48:34.077 --> 48:38.413
♪ Then I'm gonna sit right here
until I die ♪

48:38.448 --> 48:42.284
When I was in the Air Force
in Germany, in the early '50s,

48:42.319 --> 48:44.219
and trying to learn to play
the guitar,

48:44.286 --> 48:48.624
the licks I learned on the
guitar were Carter Family licks.

48:48.692 --> 48:51.626
And that carried over
into my recordings

48:51.694 --> 48:55.063
at Sun Records in 1955.

48:55.131 --> 49:00.068
♪ And I followed you, Big River,
when you called ♪

49:00.136 --> 49:02.637
FORRESTER: Johnny Cash came into
our life when he met June,

49:02.705 --> 49:06.808
and we loved him from the first
time he ever came here.

49:06.876 --> 49:09.578
June asked me to go up to see
her old home place

49:09.646 --> 49:11.647
up at Maces Springs, Virginia.

49:11.714 --> 49:13.382
You know where that is,
of course.

49:13.449 --> 49:16.484
Maces Springs,
that's near Hiltons.

49:16.586 --> 49:19.087
I remember distinctly
him coming to visit us,

49:19.155 --> 49:21.156
and I was a very little girl.

49:21.224 --> 49:25.227
And, of course, we grew up
without a lot here.

49:25.294 --> 49:26.462
I remember being worried about

49:26.529 --> 49:27.996
what we would feed him,
you know.

49:28.064 --> 49:31.733
And we went into the garden
for vegetables to fix lunch,

49:31.801 --> 49:33.368
which he loved.

49:33.403 --> 49:36.672
She says, "Well, you know where
Grandma Carter lives.

49:36.739 --> 49:38.506
Well, go over the knob

49:38.574 --> 49:42.044
and then go up Clinch Mountain
about 200 feet,

49:42.111 --> 49:44.345
and there's a whole bunch
of huckleberries."

49:44.413 --> 49:47.115
But he was so gracious
and so good to us

49:47.183 --> 49:49.117
from the very first day
we met him.

49:49.185 --> 49:51.586
I thought June was crazy.

49:51.654 --> 49:53.922
Because he wasn't --
you know, he wasn't --

49:53.989 --> 49:56.824
oh, he was nice, he's so
mannerly and everything,

49:56.892 --> 49:59.428
and I thought, "This guy..."

49:59.462 --> 50:03.031
He would look at you, and you
would be almost intimidated

50:03.099 --> 50:05.401
because you felt like
he not only was listening

50:05.468 --> 50:08.771
to you intently, he was looking
into your soul.

50:08.838 --> 50:11.774
That's why I thought,
"Gosh, what a man," you know?

50:11.841 --> 50:15.376
He's almost more than a man.

50:15.444 --> 50:21.083
♪ Now I taught the weeping
willow how to cry, cry, cry ♪

50:21.151 --> 50:24.152
He was different like A.P.
was different.

50:24.220 --> 50:26.588
They were talented people
that had been sent here

50:26.656 --> 50:29.424
that we did not understand.

50:29.492 --> 50:32.293
June would say,
"He's such a good man

50:32.362 --> 50:35.697
if he could just get
straightened out."

50:35.765 --> 50:38.400
And I thought, "June," --
I kept thinking,

50:38.468 --> 50:41.502
"You'd better wait till he gets
straightened out."

50:41.570 --> 50:43.171
She'd seen his addiction.

50:43.239 --> 50:45.140
She'd seen his marriage
fall apart, you know,

50:45.207 --> 50:46.542
with his first wife.

50:46.609 --> 50:48.943
I believe that when he asked her
to marry him

50:49.011 --> 50:52.347
that she knew full and well that
it was a dangerous proposition.

50:52.415 --> 51:00.589
♪ I am a pilgrim
and a stranger ♪

51:00.657 --> 51:07.929
♪ Just traveling through
this wearisome land ♪

51:07.997 --> 51:11.300
He was in turmoil, he was
in pain and struggle.

51:11.367 --> 51:14.436
Some people say that it was my
mother's love that saved him

51:14.504 --> 51:17.071
or turned him around
or changed his life.

51:17.140 --> 51:19.508
I think if he hadn't have
changed, he would have died,

51:19.576 --> 51:22.945
and I think it was the fear of
that in him, more than anything.

51:23.012 --> 51:24.813
But when you're at that point
in your life,

51:24.881 --> 51:27.382
and when someone is there that
loves you and that you love,

51:27.450 --> 51:29.384
that person is invaluable.

51:29.452 --> 51:31.620
And that person was my mother
to my dad.

51:31.687 --> 51:40.696
♪ I've got a home in that
yonder city, good Lord ♪

51:40.763 --> 51:43.465
SALYER: It was a round-the-clock
vigil with him.

51:43.533 --> 51:47.068
He went through hell and back
to get through that ordeal.

51:47.136 --> 51:49.304
I don't think June could have
handled that alone

51:49.372 --> 51:51.640
without some support
from her family.

51:51.708 --> 51:54.509
At times she was about ready
to give up on him.

51:54.577 --> 51:58.747
But, like June used to say,
he's worth saving.

51:58.815 --> 52:01.082
JOHN CARTER CASH:
My dad came back

52:01.150 --> 52:03.418
and found his spiritual roots

52:03.486 --> 52:06.053
in great due fact to the people
that were there to support him.

52:06.121 --> 52:09.424
Of course, my mother, but also
my mother's father, Ezra,

52:09.492 --> 52:12.226
and Maybelle, and other members
of the Carter family.

52:12.295 --> 52:15.530
♪ -- of his garment,
good Lord ♪

52:15.598 --> 52:26.574
♪ And, well, I know...
it'd make me whole ♪

52:26.642 --> 52:28.510
[ applause ]

52:28.577 --> 52:30.312
When my father began to work

52:30.379 --> 52:32.180
with Maybelle
and the Carter girls,

52:32.247 --> 52:34.482
he was attracted to them
because of their music

52:34.550 --> 52:36.718
that he'd listened to
his whole life.

52:36.786 --> 52:39.053
What he found were people
of his own kind.

52:39.121 --> 52:42.224
He found people that were
connected to him directly

52:42.291 --> 52:43.625
in a matter of heart.

52:43.693 --> 52:45.360
They were of the same heart.

52:45.427 --> 52:49.063
Mother Maybelle, Helen, Anita,
the Carter Family.

52:49.065 --> 52:53.702
[ ♪♪ ]

52:53.769 --> 52:56.504
JOHNNY CASH:
In '63, I asked June

52:56.572 --> 52:58.640
to bring her family
on the road,

52:58.708 --> 53:02.243
and she brought Mother Maybelle,
Helen, and Anita.

53:02.311 --> 53:07.348
So I had the whole Carter Family
clan on the show with me.

53:07.417 --> 53:11.720
Then in '67, June and I found
ourselves both single.

53:11.787 --> 53:15.123
So, March 1st, 1968,
we got married.

53:15.191 --> 53:17.625
And we were two peas
in a pod.

53:17.694 --> 53:19.294
We were never apart.

53:19.361 --> 53:22.730
June and I were never apart.

53:22.798 --> 53:25.833
FORRESTER: He adored
Aunt Maybelle, June's mother,

53:25.902 --> 53:28.369
I believe almost as much
as he loved June.

53:28.437 --> 53:30.705
I know that he always thought
it was awful

53:30.773 --> 53:33.074
that Aunt Maybelle had been
on the road all of her life

53:33.142 --> 53:34.676
and worked all of her life,

53:34.743 --> 53:37.712
and there was a time that she
was sitting in the hospital,

53:37.780 --> 53:39.648
you know, as a nurse's aide.

53:39.715 --> 53:41.349
And he just thought
that was horrible

53:41.417 --> 53:43.485
that she should have to do that
and work that hard,

53:43.552 --> 53:45.620
after she'd worked so hard
all of her life.

53:45.688 --> 53:48.724
JOHNNY CASH: From day one
that the Carter Family

53:48.791 --> 53:50.925
came on the road with me,

53:50.993 --> 53:56.231
Mother Maybelle Carter was like
the patron saint for all of us.

53:56.298 --> 53:59.067
Everybody respected her,
loved her,

53:59.134 --> 54:01.703
adhered to her,
tried to please her,

54:01.771 --> 54:05.139
tried to make her happy,
because she was Maybelle Carter.

54:05.207 --> 54:08.009
And she was the most V.I.P.
V.I.P.

54:08.077 --> 54:10.879
that we've ever had
on the road with us.

54:10.946 --> 54:13.482
And I have seen 'em all,

54:13.549 --> 54:15.617
I've seen 'em all,
every one of them.

54:15.685 --> 54:19.220
But Maybelle Carter was
the greatest star

54:19.289 --> 54:21.422
that I've ever known.

54:21.490 --> 54:23.225
Without being a star.

54:23.292 --> 54:25.160
Without trying to be a star.

54:25.228 --> 54:28.196
Without even wanting to be
a star.

54:35.337 --> 54:37.472
[ applause ]

54:37.540 --> 54:40.208
She taught me so much
about life, about living.

54:40.276 --> 54:42.877
And she'd passed it all
on to June.

54:42.945 --> 54:46.915
And then June had taken
her own thing, you know.

54:46.982 --> 54:51.085
June became June and Maybelle,
you know.

54:51.153 --> 54:55.490
She picked up all those songs
from her mother,

54:55.558 --> 55:00.195
and she continued to sing 'em
until the day she died.

55:00.262 --> 55:06.034
♪ I was standing by my window ♪

55:06.102 --> 55:12.107
♪ On one cold and cloudy day ♪

55:12.175 --> 55:17.812
♪ When I saw that hearse
come rolling ♪

55:17.847 --> 55:19.981
June and I would turn on
the radio,

55:20.049 --> 55:22.284
and there wouldn't be
three songs pass

55:22.286 --> 55:25.887
until June would start singing
a Carter Family song

55:25.954 --> 55:29.257
that was the same tune as
a new song that just came out.

55:29.325 --> 55:32.861
And it would blow me away
every time she would do that.

55:32.962 --> 55:36.831
It was a mean thing to do,
but it was very revealing.

55:39.802 --> 55:43.204
The old Clinch Mountain songs,
the old valley songs,

55:43.271 --> 55:46.775
the old songs from the hills
from Appalachia,

55:46.876 --> 55:49.844
down-and-out songs,
lost love songs;

55:49.911 --> 55:53.381
every one of them she sang,
she sang to me.

55:53.449 --> 55:56.417
♪ By and by, Lord, by and by ♪

55:56.485 --> 55:59.487
I don't know, God richly blessed
me for some reason.

55:59.555 --> 56:02.023
You can't chalk it up
to righteous living,

56:02.091 --> 56:05.326
because I was anything
but righteous, you know?

56:05.394 --> 56:07.128
[ chuckles ]

56:07.130 --> 56:12.100
♪ -- in the sky ♪

56:12.167 --> 56:15.370
[ cheers and applause ]

56:15.438 --> 56:17.205
ANNOUNCER: There's still a lot
of show back there,

56:17.273 --> 56:18.707
and I know you're waiting
to hear 'em.

56:18.775 --> 56:20.308
You've heard their records.

56:20.376 --> 56:22.878
Those of you who can remember
cranking your phonographs

56:22.945 --> 56:25.413
to your old RCA Victor
Victrolas

56:25.481 --> 56:27.916
will all remember
the Original Carter Family.

56:27.983 --> 56:30.485
Let's bring 'em out,
the Original Carter Family.

56:30.553 --> 56:33.655
[ cheers and applause ]

56:33.723 --> 56:36.157
A.P. CARTER: Now I guess you
people have kindly forgotten

56:36.225 --> 56:38.259
the old Carter Family name.

56:38.327 --> 56:41.463
Twenty-five years ago the Carter
Family and Jimmie Rodgers

56:41.530 --> 56:43.565
was two of the old first acts

56:43.633 --> 56:45.600
that started in Bristol,
Virginia.

56:45.668 --> 56:49.638
So we've come down here
to sing a number for you.

56:49.705 --> 56:53.909
♪ I've found a sweet haven
of sunshine at last ♪

56:53.976 --> 56:57.646
♪ And Jesus abiding above ♪

56:57.713 --> 57:01.282
FORRESTER: My grandmother never
wanted a life on the road.

57:01.350 --> 57:04.986
She did it, but it was never
as important to her.

57:05.054 --> 57:07.656
You know, she was quite content
to go off and be on her own

57:07.723 --> 57:09.257
and not be on the road.

57:09.325 --> 57:11.059
Now, Aunt Maybelle loved it.

57:11.126 --> 57:13.929
And my granddad would have
gladly done it all his life.

57:13.996 --> 57:16.565
But when the original
Carter Family broke up,

57:16.632 --> 57:18.767
it took part of my granddad's
heart.

57:18.835 --> 57:20.735
He had put so much into it

57:20.803 --> 57:25.206
that it was a very sad thing
for him.

57:25.274 --> 57:26.775
[ buzzes ]

57:26.842 --> 57:31.479
♪ I was born on the side
of Clinch Mountain ♪

57:31.547 --> 57:36.617
♪ 'Neath the beauties and
the musics of the woods ♪

57:36.685 --> 57:41.756
♪ The sweet song of the bright,
bubblin' fountain ♪

57:41.823 --> 57:46.227
♪ And the warble of the birds
I understood ♪

57:46.294 --> 57:49.631
CHARLES WOLFE: At the center
of most great creative artists

57:49.699 --> 57:51.766
is essentially a mystery.

57:51.834 --> 57:54.703
You hear today a lot about
alternate universes

57:54.770 --> 57:56.671
that are parallel to our own,

57:56.739 --> 57:59.641
and I sometimes think that
A.P. drifted in and out

57:59.709 --> 58:02.043
of one of those
alternate universes.

58:02.110 --> 58:05.513
♪ In the shadow of Clinch
Mountain I will rest ♪

58:05.581 --> 58:08.516
A.P. couldn't quite get it
out of his blood.

58:08.584 --> 58:11.252
He kept trying to do things.

58:11.320 --> 58:14.623
He wrote a book about the Bible,

58:14.690 --> 58:19.861
and he would go around to local
radio stations and buy some time

58:19.929 --> 58:22.430
and get out and sing a few songs

58:22.498 --> 58:25.934
and try to sell copies
of that book.

58:26.001 --> 58:30.805
♪ Then I asked how this green,
lofty mountain ♪

58:30.873 --> 58:36.077
♪ In the cauldron of
the lonely desert stood ♪

58:36.145 --> 58:40.681
♪ Came these words from
the bright, bubblin' fountain ♪

58:40.749 --> 58:45.686
♪ We were given by the waters
of the flood ♪

58:45.754 --> 58:49.757
♪ When I've sung my last song
in the evening ♪

58:49.825 --> 58:53.962
There was an attempt to recreate
the Carter Family in 1950.

58:54.030 --> 58:55.830
Sara and A.P. got together,

58:55.898 --> 58:57.832
and they got their kids
to sing,

58:57.900 --> 59:01.268
and they recorded a very, very
fine series of records,

59:01.336 --> 59:03.071
but nobody heard them.

59:03.138 --> 59:04.806
They weren't distributed.

59:04.873 --> 59:09.978
And it was, you know, really a
last shot for them as a family.

59:10.012 --> 59:15.183
[ whistling ]

59:15.251 --> 59:18.819
SALYER: But, you know, a long
time ago, A.P. had a vision,

59:18.888 --> 59:21.356
and he had built a stage
back in the mountain

59:21.423 --> 59:23.758
that he was gonna start
making music.

59:23.825 --> 59:25.826
JANETTE CARTER:
Well, he put a stage up

59:25.895 --> 59:28.329
and tried to have
some programs there,

59:28.397 --> 59:30.731
but he didn't have no fence.

59:30.833 --> 59:33.468
And the people, they just
walked in off the road,

59:33.536 --> 59:35.803
come out of the woods,
or anywhere.

59:35.871 --> 59:37.938
You know, he couldn't make
no money like that.

59:38.006 --> 59:40.008
That fell through.

59:40.076 --> 59:42.943
SALYER: I remember taking A.P.
to Kingsport

59:43.011 --> 59:44.945
when they had the old
Gem Theatre over there,

59:45.013 --> 59:48.015
and Helen and Anita and June
and all of them were playing.

59:48.050 --> 59:50.452
He wasn't into music then,
and it was really sad.

59:50.519 --> 59:53.020
He was sad.
His life was sad at that time.

59:53.088 --> 59:55.857
And they put him onstage
and let him talk a little bit,

59:55.924 --> 59:57.726
and he got to emcee the program.

59:57.793 --> 01:00:00.294
He was just thrilled to do that.

01:00:00.363 --> 01:00:03.832
He was getting older then,
and he wasn't very well.

01:00:03.899 --> 01:00:06.401
And he slept down there
in the store a lot, I think.

01:00:06.469 --> 01:00:07.935
He just had a bed down there,

01:00:08.003 --> 01:00:09.437
and he just stayed down there
at night,

01:00:09.505 --> 01:00:12.874
because I guess that's what
he wanted to do.

01:00:12.941 --> 01:00:15.477
JANETTE CARTER: And then Daddy
moved in with me,

01:00:15.544 --> 01:00:18.380
where he was sick
and in bad health.

01:00:18.447 --> 01:00:22.717
And the last three years
of his life was here,

01:00:22.784 --> 01:00:26.254
at this house.

01:00:26.288 --> 01:00:30.358
FLO WOLFE: One day he was
feeling really, really bad,

01:00:30.426 --> 01:00:32.927
and the record player
was in the living room,

01:00:32.994 --> 01:00:35.763
and we'd set up a bed for him
in the dining room,

01:00:35.831 --> 01:00:37.665
near the bathroom.

01:00:37.733 --> 01:00:40.535
And he wanted to --
it was "Jealous Hearted Me."

01:00:40.602 --> 01:00:41.669
I don't know why that song.

01:00:41.737 --> 01:00:43.504
He wanted that played
all day long,

01:00:43.572 --> 01:00:46.340
just as loud as it could play.

01:00:46.408 --> 01:00:49.377
♪ Takes a rocking chair to rock
takes a rubber ball to roll ♪

01:00:49.444 --> 01:00:52.446
♪ Takes the man I love
to satisfy my soul ♪

01:00:52.514 --> 01:00:58.252
♪ Because I'm jealous,
jealous hearted me ♪

01:00:58.320 --> 01:01:03.992
♪ I said I'm jealous,
jealous as I can be ♪

01:01:04.060 --> 01:01:06.928
I know Mother said, "Well,
I don't know what the neighbors

01:01:06.995 --> 01:01:09.464
are thinking and people going
up and down the road,"

01:01:09.531 --> 01:01:11.566
but we played that over and over
that day.

01:01:11.633 --> 01:01:13.901
That's just something
he wanted to hear.

01:01:13.936 --> 01:01:16.805
He was in love with Sara
until the day he died.

01:01:16.872 --> 01:01:21.175
He always hoped that Sara
would come back.

01:01:21.243 --> 01:01:23.311
It was a dream he had.

01:01:23.378 --> 01:01:25.613
And he talked about it a lot.

01:01:25.681 --> 01:01:29.016
Toward the end, his mind
was not very good,

01:01:29.084 --> 01:01:32.186
and he thought he was back
on border radio.

01:01:32.253 --> 01:01:34.221
And he had my mom and --

01:01:34.289 --> 01:01:38.225
(voice breaks)
and Bill Clifton sing,

01:01:38.293 --> 01:01:41.863
and he would think
he was doing shows,

01:01:41.930 --> 01:01:46.367
and they'd humor him
and they sang.

01:01:48.537 --> 01:01:52.173
JANETTE CARTER: Days before
he died, I was in bed.

01:01:52.241 --> 01:01:54.208
And he said, "You come in here,
Janette.

01:01:54.276 --> 01:01:56.110
I want to talk to you."

01:01:56.178 --> 01:01:57.278
So I went in there.

01:01:57.346 --> 01:02:00.548
And he said, "I wanted
to ask you something."

01:02:00.615 --> 01:02:03.551
He said, "I want you
to promise me

01:02:03.618 --> 01:02:06.887
that my music
will be carried on."

01:02:06.955 --> 01:02:09.323
And I said, "Daddy, how in
the world I'm gonna do it,

01:02:09.391 --> 01:02:10.791
I don't know."

01:02:10.859 --> 01:02:13.394
I've got little children
I was trying to raise.

01:02:13.462 --> 01:02:16.364
And I said, "But I will try."

01:02:16.432 --> 01:02:18.432
And I says, "I'll never do
nothing

01:02:18.500 --> 01:02:21.969
that brings dishonor
to my people or to you."

01:02:22.037 --> 01:02:24.905
So I made two vows.

01:02:24.973 --> 01:02:28.109
And I've kept 'em both.

01:02:28.176 --> 01:02:32.747
♪ Out that gate I have passed
since my childhood ♪

01:02:32.814 --> 01:02:37.885
♪ Over the railway through
the tunnel to the west ♪

01:02:37.953 --> 01:02:43.023
♪ Singing songs of the
Clinch Mountain wild wood ♪

01:02:43.091 --> 01:02:47.829
♪ Songs that people, birds,
and flowers love the best ♪

01:02:47.896 --> 01:02:49.797
[ whistling ]

01:02:49.865 --> 01:02:51.532
FORRESTER:
I worshipped my granddad.

01:02:51.600 --> 01:02:54.468
Every step he took,
I'd try to take one behind him.

01:02:54.536 --> 01:02:57.872
And I -- Lord, I miss him.

01:02:57.940 --> 01:03:02.610
I do feel like he probably
never realized what he had done

01:03:02.677 --> 01:03:05.213
or his contributions to music.

01:03:05.281 --> 01:03:07.815
He would have been
bowled over by the fact

01:03:07.883 --> 01:03:10.350
that his face was
on a postage stamp.

01:03:10.418 --> 01:03:13.320
He would have got
a kick out of that.

01:03:13.388 --> 01:03:14.455
What's the name of the cemetery?

01:03:14.523 --> 01:03:16.524
- Mount Vernon.
- Mount Vernon Cemetery.

01:03:16.592 --> 01:03:19.527
We drove up this
winding gravel road,

01:03:19.595 --> 01:03:23.364
and the tall pines
all the way around,

01:03:23.432 --> 01:03:26.367
and there was one little spot
of sunlight way down at the end.

01:03:26.434 --> 01:03:29.070
Well, we walked
right straight to it,

01:03:29.137 --> 01:03:31.072
and I said,
"That's it, June."

01:03:31.140 --> 01:03:32.340
She had never seen it either.

01:03:32.408 --> 01:03:34.008
She'd heard about it,
she knew about it.

01:03:34.075 --> 01:03:35.676
I walked around,

01:03:35.744 --> 01:03:40.948
and right where the sun
was streaming down

01:03:41.016 --> 01:03:43.551
on this rose marble,

01:03:43.618 --> 01:03:46.454
the words said, "A.P. Carter,"

01:03:46.522 --> 01:03:50.457
and a gold record under that,
and under that,

01:03:50.526 --> 01:03:52.793
"Keep on the Sunny Side."

01:03:52.861 --> 01:03:56.364
FORRESTER: He wanted a
particular type of headstone,

01:03:56.431 --> 01:03:57.965
because he told his children,

01:03:58.032 --> 01:03:59.634
he said, "You know,
people will come,

01:03:59.701 --> 01:04:03.103
and they'll be coming
to see my grave."

01:04:05.674 --> 01:04:10.511
♪ When I've sung my last song
in the evening ♪

01:04:10.579 --> 01:04:15.583
♪ And the sun sets
in the golden west ♪

01:04:15.651 --> 01:04:20.288
♪ All the things of this world
I'll be leaving ♪

01:04:20.355 --> 01:04:26.627
♪ In the shadow of Clinch
Mountain, I will rest ♪

01:04:26.695 --> 01:04:30.564
[ ♪♪ ]

01:04:35.003 --> 01:04:37.204
JOHN CARTER CASH:
My mother and her sisters

01:04:37.272 --> 01:04:39.973
moved on to different parts
of their life.

01:04:40.041 --> 01:04:41.776
And I think Maybelle,
at that point,

01:04:41.843 --> 01:04:45.045
was a little bit lost
about what she was gonna do.

01:04:45.113 --> 01:04:46.380
I think Ezra
would have been fine

01:04:46.448 --> 01:04:47.715
with her deciding, you know,

01:04:47.782 --> 01:04:49.550
that she was gonna retire
and take it easy.

01:04:49.617 --> 01:04:51.953
Bought a place down in Florida
that sat right on the river.

01:04:52.020 --> 01:04:54.021
And they both loved to fish
and whatnot.

01:04:54.089 --> 01:04:57.591
But Maybelle could not
give up music.

01:04:57.659 --> 01:05:01.795
[ ♪♪ ]

01:05:01.863 --> 01:05:03.631
SEEGER:
The New Lost City Ramblers

01:05:03.698 --> 01:05:06.434
got together as just
an informal meeting

01:05:06.502 --> 01:05:08.836
on a radio program,

01:05:08.903 --> 01:05:12.906
and we all shared a love
for old-time music and singing.

01:05:12.974 --> 01:05:15.743
♪ Black Jack Davey come a-ridi''
through the woods ♪

01:05:15.811 --> 01:05:18.746
♪ Sang so loud and gaily ♪

01:05:18.813 --> 01:05:21.348
♪ Made the hills
around him ring ♪

01:05:21.416 --> 01:05:24.118
♪ And he charmed the heart
of a lady ♪

01:05:24.186 --> 01:05:26.988
♪ Charmed the heart
of a lady ♪

01:05:27.055 --> 01:05:28.890
Out in the West Coast,
there was a place

01:05:28.957 --> 01:05:32.493
called the Ash Grove
in Hollywood, where we worked

01:05:32.560 --> 01:05:36.430
to bring traditional musicians
to urban audiences.

01:05:36.498 --> 01:05:40.435
And one of those was
Maybelle Carter.

01:05:40.502 --> 01:05:45.272
When I first contacted Maybelle,
I had the feeling at the time

01:05:45.340 --> 01:05:48.776
that she was relatively
inactive musically.

01:05:48.844 --> 01:05:52.380
She was working
as a kind of a nurse.

01:05:52.447 --> 01:05:56.383
She was double-booked
the first two or three days,

01:05:56.451 --> 01:06:01.189
so she sent a substitute in,
and that was Johnny Cash.

01:06:01.256 --> 01:06:06.160
And Johnny played
as opening act for us.

01:06:06.227 --> 01:06:09.430
But at the Ash Grove, of course
they -- they loved her.

01:06:09.498 --> 01:06:13.267
And people would bring in
records for her to autograph.

01:06:13.335 --> 01:06:17.671
We traveled with Maybelle,
and she regaled us with stories

01:06:17.739 --> 01:06:20.608
of Nashville artists
that were flipping out

01:06:20.675 --> 01:06:23.377
and that she helped make it
through the night.

01:06:23.445 --> 01:06:25.045
They'd call her up
in the middle of the night

01:06:25.113 --> 01:06:29.082
and say,
"Momma, I need to talk."

01:06:31.219 --> 01:06:33.620
I played a lot of colleges,
you know,

01:06:33.688 --> 01:06:36.424
and, oh, just in a lot
of different places,

01:06:36.491 --> 01:06:39.293
Newport Folk Festival
and a gang of them.

01:06:39.361 --> 01:06:41.862
I would have never believed it
till I done it,

01:06:41.930 --> 01:06:43.897
but sometimes I'd do
three shows a night,

01:06:43.965 --> 01:06:45.966
an hour show each one.

01:06:46.034 --> 01:06:49.604
♪ I went across the river
and I laid down to sleep ♪

01:06:49.671 --> 01:06:52.072
And I had my banjo,
and I had my guitar,

01:06:52.140 --> 01:06:53.408
and I had my autoharp.

01:06:53.475 --> 01:06:55.242
I played everything I knew.

01:06:55.310 --> 01:06:56.977
[ laughs ]

01:06:57.045 --> 01:06:58.979
But they enjoyed it,
and they just

01:06:59.047 --> 01:07:01.248
a wonderful audience
to work for.

01:07:01.316 --> 01:07:07.188
Of course, that's aboutn
the only people that I had

01:07:07.255 --> 01:07:09.123
was the college kids, you know.

01:07:09.191 --> 01:07:11.792
♪ It takes a worried man
to sing a worried song ♪

01:07:11.860 --> 01:07:15.963
♪ I'm worried now,
but I won't be worried long ♪

01:07:16.031 --> 01:07:17.097
She was the experimenter.

01:07:17.165 --> 01:07:19.033
She was the progressive.

01:07:19.100 --> 01:07:21.436
She had a lovely laugh.

01:07:21.503 --> 01:07:23.538
She had a good sense of humor.

01:07:23.605 --> 01:07:26.006
She wanted to be
one of the boys.

01:07:26.074 --> 01:07:29.276
She seemed to take life
as it came.

01:07:29.344 --> 01:07:34.248
MAYBELLE CARTER:
[ laughing ]

01:07:34.316 --> 01:07:36.317
Oh, me.

01:07:36.384 --> 01:07:38.619
[ ♪♪ ]

01:07:38.687 --> 01:07:40.888
DAVIS: I was 13 when
we started working the road

01:07:40.956 --> 01:07:43.491
with Grandma, and it was
a totally different audience

01:07:43.559 --> 01:07:45.826
than she had played to
the years before.

01:07:45.894 --> 01:07:47.494
And they were mostly young,

01:07:47.562 --> 01:07:49.229
long-haired hippie people,
you know.

01:07:49.231 --> 01:07:52.199
♪ One toke over the line,
sweet Jesus ♪

01:07:52.267 --> 01:07:55.436
♪ One toke over the line ♪

01:07:55.503 --> 01:07:57.905
"What were they smoking
out there?" is what she'd say.

01:07:57.972 --> 01:07:59.173
[ laughs ]

01:07:59.240 --> 01:08:02.542
And she wanted to record
"One Toke Over the Line."

01:08:02.610 --> 01:08:05.212
She thought that that was
a really good gospel song

01:08:05.280 --> 01:08:08.782
because that it said "one toke
over the line, sweet Jesus."

01:08:08.850 --> 01:08:11.686
She wanted to put that
in the Carter Family show.

01:08:11.753 --> 01:08:13.587
And we had to explain to her,
"No, you don't want to.

01:08:13.655 --> 01:08:15.422
No, Grandma,
that won't work.

01:08:15.490 --> 01:08:16.890
That won't work."

01:08:16.957 --> 01:08:20.261
And I always knew my grandma
had it going on, you know.

01:08:20.328 --> 01:08:24.631
But to cause an audience of
these pot-smoking college kids

01:08:24.698 --> 01:08:27.435
to suddenly stand up just when
she walked on the stage,

01:08:27.502 --> 01:08:30.004
it didn't really dawn on me
till then

01:08:30.071 --> 01:08:32.839
that it was such a big deal.

01:08:32.907 --> 01:08:36.911
♪ One toke, one toke
over the line ♪

01:08:36.978 --> 01:08:40.881
[ ♪♪ ]

01:08:47.622 --> 01:08:51.758
♪ Oh, tell me, sweet Fern,
is he thinking of me ♪

01:08:51.827 --> 01:08:56.162
♪ And the promise
he made long ago ♪

01:08:56.231 --> 01:09:00.434
♪ He said he'd return
from over the sea ♪

01:09:00.501 --> 01:09:04.638
♪ Oh, why do the earth
roll so slow ♪

01:09:04.706 --> 01:09:08.175
FORRESTER: I imagine the last
part of her life was spent

01:09:08.243 --> 01:09:11.145
wishing that she was here
with her kids,

01:09:11.212 --> 01:09:15.182
right where she started out,
and not so far away from them.

01:09:15.250 --> 01:09:20.154
You know, she made a visit
back here at least once a year.

01:09:20.221 --> 01:09:22.122
Mainly because we didn't
see her that much,

01:09:22.189 --> 01:09:24.058
it was like royalty
came to town.

01:09:24.126 --> 01:09:25.426
And I know I went up to her

01:09:25.493 --> 01:09:27.394
and I just hung around her knees
and looked at her.

01:09:27.462 --> 01:09:29.129
And she let me look
at her rings,

01:09:29.197 --> 01:09:30.932
and she had her nails polished,
and I thought,

01:09:30.999 --> 01:09:32.966
"Gosh, these nails are pretty."

01:09:33.035 --> 01:09:35.002
And I loved to hear her talk.

01:09:35.069 --> 01:09:36.970
You know, when she started
talking,

01:09:37.037 --> 01:09:39.774
you knew where that beautiful
voice she had was coming from.

01:09:39.841 --> 01:09:42.475
And she could almost walk
in a room and say something,

01:09:42.544 --> 01:09:43.944
and everybody would
just quiet down.

01:09:44.011 --> 01:09:46.514
It was just like she put
some kind of a spell over them

01:09:46.581 --> 01:09:47.848
with her voice.

01:09:47.881 --> 01:09:52.486
♪ I know he's away
in a far distant land ♪

01:09:52.554 --> 01:09:56.624
♪ A land that's over the sea ♪

01:09:56.692 --> 01:10:01.128
If I had to, like, title her,
I'd have to call her Queen.

01:10:01.195 --> 01:10:04.531
That's how she hit you,
like a queen.

01:10:04.599 --> 01:10:07.534
♪ Sweet Fern ♪
♪ Sweet Fern ♪

01:10:07.602 --> 01:10:09.937
♪ Sweet Fern ♪
♪ Sweet Fern ♪

01:10:10.005 --> 01:10:14.241
♪ Oh, tell me,
is my darling still true ♪

01:10:14.276 --> 01:10:16.543
FORRESTER: For the most part,
the end of her life

01:10:16.612 --> 01:10:18.913
was not about music.

01:10:18.981 --> 01:10:21.983
She had pretty well
left all that behind.

01:10:22.050 --> 01:10:24.585
She did some concerts
in the '60s, you know,

01:10:24.653 --> 01:10:26.520
but I don't think
she ever really missed

01:10:26.588 --> 01:10:28.055
doing the music that much.

01:10:28.122 --> 01:10:29.957
She would do it and she had fun
when she did it,

01:10:30.025 --> 01:10:32.059
but I think she was happy
to be private

01:10:32.127 --> 01:10:33.927
in the last part of her life.

01:10:33.995 --> 01:10:37.264
And I think she was surprised,
too, by some of the things

01:10:37.332 --> 01:10:39.367
that she and Aunt Maybelle
got to see.

01:10:39.434 --> 01:10:41.902
Certainly the induction
into the Hall of Fame,

01:10:41.970 --> 01:10:44.838
they were very surprised
by that.

01:10:44.906 --> 01:10:47.507
And she always loved to be
around Aunt Maybelle.

01:10:47.575 --> 01:10:51.178
They were buddies
to the very end.

01:10:51.246 --> 01:10:53.914
♪ Sweet Fern ♪
♪ Sweet Fern ♪

01:10:53.982 --> 01:10:56.783
Of course, she was living
in California when she died,

01:10:56.852 --> 01:10:59.019
and she wanted to be back here,

01:10:59.087 --> 01:11:02.589
and, of course, they did bring
her back here to bury her.

01:11:02.657 --> 01:11:06.693
But I imagine her life was even
lonelier than my grandad's.

01:11:06.761 --> 01:11:09.763
Sadly, I imagine
that's the case.

01:11:09.831 --> 01:11:13.033
[ ♪♪ ]

01:11:19.941 --> 01:11:22.175
[ ♪♪ ]

01:11:22.243 --> 01:11:24.344
PETE SEEGER (on recording):
To play an endless series

01:11:24.412 --> 01:11:26.146
of chords on the guitar

01:11:26.214 --> 01:11:28.883
can, in the end,
be very, very boring.

01:11:28.950 --> 01:11:30.717
You'll find it
a lot more interesting

01:11:30.785 --> 01:11:32.853
to introduce melodies
and countermelodies

01:11:32.920 --> 01:11:35.356
in the bass strings,
like many of the songs

01:11:35.423 --> 01:11:37.791
recorded by the famous
country music group

01:11:37.859 --> 01:11:40.027
the Carter Family.

01:11:40.094 --> 01:11:41.795
HANNA:
I remember having an LP

01:11:41.863 --> 01:11:44.398
that was a Pete Seeger
instruction course.

01:11:44.466 --> 01:11:46.200
And there was
a Maybelle Carter thing

01:11:46.268 --> 01:11:48.435
on how to learn
the Carter Scratch,

01:11:48.503 --> 01:11:52.072
which combines rhythm
and melody, you know.

01:11:52.140 --> 01:11:54.908
And this is my awkward
version of it.

01:11:54.976 --> 01:11:58.812
[ plays ]

01:12:02.216 --> 01:12:04.985
You know, which I'm still
fumbling around,

01:12:05.052 --> 01:12:06.019
trying to learn it.

01:12:06.087 --> 01:12:07.755
Sorry, Pete.
Sorry, Maybelle.

01:12:07.789 --> 01:12:12.626
[ ♪♪ ]

01:12:19.067 --> 01:12:24.137
♪ Oh, I'll pawn you
my gold watch and chain, love ♪

01:12:24.205 --> 01:12:30.144
♪ And I'll pawn you
my gold diamond ring ♪

01:12:30.212 --> 01:12:35.949
♪ I will pawn you
this heart in my bosom ♪

01:12:36.017 --> 01:12:40.754
♪ Only say that
you'll love me again ♪

01:12:40.822 --> 01:12:44.925
I play guitar and sing
for the Nitty Gritty Dirt Band.

01:12:44.993 --> 01:12:47.394
We were these hippies
from the West Coast,

01:12:47.462 --> 01:12:49.596
and also little folk puppies.

01:12:49.664 --> 01:12:52.132
And we wondered about places
like West Virginia

01:12:52.200 --> 01:12:53.734
and Tennesse and Virginia.

01:12:53.802 --> 01:12:56.236
And it was like, wow,
we need to go there.

01:12:56.303 --> 01:12:58.405
[ laughs ]
And eventually, we did.

01:12:58.472 --> 01:13:02.242
[ "Will the Circle Be Unbroken"
plays ]

01:13:06.280 --> 01:13:08.916
One of the things that I loved
about doing The Circle Project

01:13:08.983 --> 01:13:13.853
was we were making music
with Doc Watson, Merle Travis,

01:13:13.921 --> 01:13:18.225
and Earl Scruggs, Jimmy Martin,
and Maybelle Carter.

01:13:18.293 --> 01:13:23.096
♪ I was standing by my window ♪

01:13:23.165 --> 01:13:28.101
♪ On one cold and cloudy day ♪

01:13:28.170 --> 01:13:30.437
You know, we were operating
on a combination

01:13:30.505 --> 01:13:32.706
of fear and excitement and joy,

01:13:32.774 --> 01:13:35.342
all kind of bundled in together
during these sessions,

01:13:35.410 --> 01:13:37.578
because we were thrilled
that we were there,

01:13:37.646 --> 01:13:40.781
but we were also scared to death
that we'd better play okay.

01:13:40.849 --> 01:13:42.416
What Maybelle brought
to the session,

01:13:42.483 --> 01:13:45.152
aside from her wealth
of talent,

01:13:45.220 --> 01:13:49.323
was just this great sort of
spiritual calming.

01:13:49.391 --> 01:13:54.027
She was just so like, "Boys,
it's no big deal," you know?

01:13:54.095 --> 01:13:56.363
I think what came out
of those sessions

01:13:56.431 --> 01:13:59.733
was that there were these
two gaps that were bridged:

01:13:59.801 --> 01:14:03.470
a generation gap
and also the cultural gap.

01:14:03.538 --> 01:14:06.273
You know, it was peace marches
and Nixon,

01:14:06.340 --> 01:14:08.275
and, you know, the country
was divided.

01:14:08.342 --> 01:14:10.277
Imagine that.

01:14:10.311 --> 01:14:12.112
A lot of people looked at it
and thought,

01:14:12.180 --> 01:14:13.514
"Well, this is really illogical

01:14:13.581 --> 01:14:15.482
that these guys are
playing together."

01:14:15.550 --> 01:14:18.519
This was also around the time
of the film Easy Rider.

01:14:18.587 --> 01:14:22.890
So we're thinking, "Oh, man,
the guys that shot Peter Fonda

01:14:22.958 --> 01:14:25.125
look just like those guys
that we're going to Nashville

01:14:25.193 --> 01:14:26.827
to record with."

01:14:26.894 --> 01:14:30.597
Of course, the element
that wiped out

01:14:30.665 --> 01:14:33.066
all of that misconception
was the music.

01:14:33.134 --> 01:14:36.703
It helped take away some of
the prejudice on both sides.

01:14:36.771 --> 01:14:38.938
MAYBELLE CARTER:
Since I did this thing

01:14:39.006 --> 01:14:41.275
with the Nitty Gritty Dirt Band,

01:14:41.342 --> 01:14:43.710
you know, this
"Will the Circle Be Unbroken,"

01:14:43.778 --> 01:14:46.880
that was the biggest surprise
of my life

01:14:46.947 --> 01:14:48.748
of ever doing anything
like that.

01:14:48.816 --> 01:14:50.417
[ laughter ]

01:14:50.485 --> 01:14:52.686
But then when I got
the nomination

01:14:52.753 --> 01:14:54.954
for the Grammy Award, I thought,

01:14:55.022 --> 01:14:58.492
"Well, this is not happening
to me here," you know?

01:14:58.560 --> 01:15:00.728
She used to call us
"them dirty boys," by the way.

01:15:00.795 --> 01:15:03.096
That's what June told us,
which I loved.

01:15:03.164 --> 01:15:06.099
She said, "You know, Momma
always called you guys

01:15:06.167 --> 01:15:07.701
'them dirty boys.'"

01:15:07.769 --> 01:15:09.369
And I thought that was
the sweetest.

01:15:09.437 --> 01:15:12.006
[ laughs ]

01:15:14.776 --> 01:15:16.577
One, two, three.

01:15:16.644 --> 01:15:21.682
[ ♪♪ ]

01:15:26.687 --> 01:15:32.259
♪ Out here the hearts
of men are failing ♪

01:15:32.327 --> 01:15:37.430
♪ For these are latter days
I know ♪

01:15:37.498 --> 01:15:42.635
♪ The Great Depression
now is spreading ♪

01:15:42.703 --> 01:15:47.907
♪ God's word declared
it would be so ♪

01:15:47.975 --> 01:15:53.247
♪ I'm going where
there's no depression ♪

01:15:53.314 --> 01:15:58.585
♪ To the lovely land
that's free from care ♪

01:15:58.653 --> 01:16:03.757
♪ I'll leave this world
of toil and trouble ♪

01:16:03.825 --> 01:16:10.197
♪ My home's in heaven,
I'm going there ♪

01:16:10.264 --> 01:16:13.500
I remembered
what my daddy told me.

01:16:13.568 --> 01:16:16.570
He wished I'd try
to carry on the music.

01:16:16.638 --> 01:16:19.740
And the idea struck me.

01:16:19.808 --> 01:16:21.775
I said, "You know what
I'm gonna do?"

01:16:21.843 --> 01:16:25.245
I said, "I'm gonna quit my job
as a cook at the school

01:16:25.313 --> 01:16:28.682
and I'm gonna start
music gatherings."

01:16:28.750 --> 01:16:31.785
I said, "We're gonna start
tearing that store up,

01:16:31.853 --> 01:16:35.155
putting in bleachers
and getting it all set up."

01:16:35.222 --> 01:16:39.492
And my children thought
I was losing my mind, I think.

01:16:39.560 --> 01:16:41.695
Then I called the papers

01:16:41.763 --> 01:16:44.230
and I said what
I was fixin' to do.

01:16:44.298 --> 01:16:47.834
And I said, "I'd be glad
for you to write an article."

01:16:47.902 --> 01:16:50.771
They said, "Well, Ms. Carter,
we sure will."

01:16:50.839 --> 01:16:55.108
I remember that first
Saturday night

01:16:55.176 --> 01:16:59.045
I was sitting down there
on the porch by myself,

01:16:59.113 --> 01:17:02.282
looking for the cars
to come up the road.

01:17:02.350 --> 01:17:06.553
I thought, "Well, Lord, God,
there may not be nobody come."

01:17:06.621 --> 01:17:11.525
I thought, "Well, I told Daddy
what I'd do."

01:17:11.592 --> 01:17:14.594
And I said, "Now, God,
I'll tell you,

01:17:14.663 --> 01:17:16.229
me and you'll have a talk.

01:17:16.297 --> 01:17:18.932
I'm gonna tell you
what I'm gonna do."

01:17:19.000 --> 01:17:23.269
And I says, "I'm gonna have
a program every Saturday night.

01:17:23.337 --> 01:17:26.740
I'm gonna try
to carry on the music."

01:17:26.808 --> 01:17:30.577
And then I saw the cars
a-comin' up the road.

01:17:30.645 --> 01:17:35.515
[ ♪♪ ]

01:17:46.694 --> 01:17:48.796
♪ Down the road, down the road ♪

01:17:48.863 --> 01:17:50.964
♪ Got a pretty girl
down the road ♪

01:17:51.032 --> 01:17:54.034
[ ♪♪ ]

01:17:54.101 --> 01:17:55.903
JOE CARTER:
I give it the name

01:17:56.037 --> 01:17:58.738
the Carter Family Fold.

01:17:58.807 --> 01:18:03.877
A lot of people has asked me
what the "fold" signifies.

01:18:03.945 --> 01:18:06.312
And I told them that
just like in the Bible,

01:18:06.380 --> 01:18:10.150
the sheep's fold,
it's a place of refuge.

01:18:10.218 --> 01:18:15.422
[ ♪♪ ]

01:18:15.489 --> 01:18:18.892
JANETTE CARTER: From the start,
I just had control.

01:18:18.960 --> 01:18:23.096
And if any band ever comes
under the influence of alcohol

01:18:23.164 --> 01:18:26.466
and get up on the stage
and tell dirty jokes,

01:18:26.534 --> 01:18:28.201
I stop it.

01:18:28.269 --> 01:18:31.638
Or if they just start dancing
that ain't very becoming,

01:18:31.706 --> 01:18:33.973
I stop that.

01:18:34.041 --> 01:18:36.676
I think everybody down here's
kindly afraid of me.

01:18:36.744 --> 01:18:38.678
[ laughs ]

01:18:38.746 --> 01:18:44.350
♪ Keep on the sunny side,
always on the sunny side ♪

01:18:44.418 --> 01:18:47.253
MAN: My mother achieved
her own bit of fame

01:18:47.322 --> 01:18:50.657
with the Fold and become
somewhat of an icon.

01:18:50.725 --> 01:18:53.160
Well, I grew up around it,

01:18:53.227 --> 01:18:55.462
and there was always a guitar
leaning in the corner

01:18:55.530 --> 01:18:58.465
or an autoharp or there was
music all around me,

01:18:58.532 --> 01:19:00.200
but I just took it for granted

01:19:00.268 --> 01:19:02.102
and never paid much
attention to it

01:19:02.170 --> 01:19:04.671
until Mother started having
the shows here.

01:19:04.738 --> 01:19:06.573
And then I started
really understanding

01:19:06.640 --> 01:19:08.308
how much I appreciated
the music.

01:19:08.376 --> 01:19:12.846
♪ Keep on the sunny side
of life ♪

01:19:12.913 --> 01:19:17.550
[ music playing
and dancers tapping ]

01:19:17.618 --> 01:19:19.653
JANETTE CARTER:
We've been having concerts

01:19:19.721 --> 01:19:23.390
at the Carter Fold building
for 30 years.

01:19:23.458 --> 01:19:27.360
My children say they'll keep
the music a-goin'.

01:19:27.428 --> 01:19:31.231
Like I tell them,
they're young and I'm old,

01:19:31.299 --> 01:19:34.334
and music will change.

01:19:34.402 --> 01:19:37.137
And I said,
"You may wanna change."

01:19:37.205 --> 01:19:40.440
But I said, "You'd better do
what I tell you,"

01:19:40.507 --> 01:19:43.409
just to keep them
big doors open.

01:19:43.477 --> 01:19:46.980
And I'm quite sure they will.

01:19:47.048 --> 01:19:49.850
[ cheers and applause ]

01:19:51.752 --> 01:19:55.388
[ ♪♪ ]

01:19:55.456 --> 01:20:00.794
[ children playing ]

01:20:00.862 --> 01:20:02.829
[ ♪♪ ]

01:20:02.897 --> 01:20:04.164
JOHN CARTER CASH:
Tonight, here at

01:20:04.231 --> 01:20:06.066
the American Roots Music
Festival,

01:20:06.134 --> 01:20:09.903
is the first time
that my cousin Dale and I

01:20:09.971 --> 01:20:12.138
and our wives,
along with Larry Perkins,

01:20:12.206 --> 01:20:14.074
are getting to perform together.

01:20:14.141 --> 01:20:16.910
And I guess we have the audacity
to call ourselves

01:20:16.978 --> 01:20:19.379
the Carter Family.
[ laughs ]

